{{Refimprove|date=October 2014}}
Within the field of [[anthropology]] and other [[social science]]s, [[ethnography]] is a form of research that relies on a range of sources of data, but usually tends to rely mainly on [[participant observation]]. However, the term also refers to the product of this type of research, which of course normally takes a textual form. As a result, ethnography is also sometimes seen as a ''genre of writing, one'' used to describe patterns of human social interaction in particular contexts.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Works and Lives: The anthropologist as author|last=Geertz|first=Clifford|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1988|isbn=|location=Stanford CA|pages=}}</ref>
Within the context of ethnography, the term 'realism' is often used to refer to the assumptions that some kinds of ethnographic work make about the phenomena to be investigated, and how these are to be understood. However, 'ethnographic realism' has also been used to refer to a style of writing that narrates the author's experiences and observations as if the reader were witnessing or experiencing events first hand. A work written using ethnographic realism may be referred to as a '''realist ethnography''', and classified as a subgenre of ethnography.
==Styles of ethnographic realism== George Marcus and Dick Cushman described and categorized realist ethnographies under certain characteristics.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Marcus|first1=George|last2=Cushman|first2=Dick|title=Ethnographies as Texts|journal=Annual Review of Anthropology|date=Jan 1, 1982|volume=11|pages=25–69|jstor=2155775|doi=10.1146/annurev.an.11.100182.000325}}</ref> *Totalizing description *Omniscient narration *Native interpretation *Generalizations *Jargon
==References== {{Reflist}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethnographic Realism}} [[Category:Anthropology]] [[Category:Ethnography]] [[Category:Realism]]
{{Anthropology-stub}}

{{Infobox Military Structure |name= Jasmuiža Manor |partof= |location=Latgale, Latvia |coordinates= |image=Jasmuiža - Raiņa muzejs Aizkalnē 2001-04-08.jpg |image_size=280px |caption=Rainis memorial museum "Jasmuiža" |image2= |caption2= |type=Manor |code= |built= 1891 |builder= |materials= |height= |used= |demolished= |condition= |ownership= |open_to_public= |controlledby= |garrison= |current_commander= |commanders= |occupants= |battles= |events= }}
'''Jasmuiža Manor''' is a manor in the historical region of [[Latgale]], in [[Latvia]], currently a [[writer's home museum]] dedicated to [[Rainis]].
==History== Construction of the wooden manor house near Aizkalne began in 1883 and was completed in 1891.<ref name=LPMA>{{cite web|last=Latvijas Piļu un Muižu asociācija|title=Jasmuiža|url=http://www.pilis.lv/a_pnm/view.php?id=40&prop_id=168|publisher=Latvijas Piļu un Muižu asociācija|accessdate=17 August 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119140521/http://www.pilis.lv/a_pnm/view.php?id=40&prop_id=168|archivedate=19 November 2015|df=}}</ref> The [[writer's home museum|building now houses a museum]] open on 16 August 1964,<ref name=MMA>{{cite web|last=Memoriālo muzeju apvienība|title=Raiņa muzejs "Jasmuiža"|url=http://memorialiemuzeji.lv/muzeji/raina-un-aspazijas-muzejs/raina-muzejs-jasmuiza/|publisher=Memoriālo muzeju apvienība|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref> dedicated to the Latvian writer [[Rainis]] whose father, Krišjānis Pliekšāns, managed the surrounding estate.<ref>{{cite book|last=Zarāns|first=Alberts|title=Latvijas pilis un muižas. Castles and manors of Latvia| language=Latvian, English|publisher=|location=Riga|series=|year=2006|isbn=9984-785-05-X|oclc=72358861}}</ref>
==See also== *[[List of palaces and manor houses in Latvia]]
